WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.140
Today, the question is, are we ready to routinely treat smoldering multiple myeloma?

00:00:05.880 --> 00:00:07.640
Very hot debate.

00:00:07.740 --> 00:00:09.500
These are my disclosures.

00:00:10.040 --> 00:00:14.300
Remember, when we're talking about smoldering myeloma, the current definition of smoldering

00:00:14.300 --> 00:00:21.680
myeloma is between 10% and 60% plasma cells since the Slim Crab revision, or an M-spike

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:27.740
of 3 grams per deciliter, or 24-hour Bench Jones protein of 500 milligrams, and absolutely

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:30.780
no myeloma-defining symptoms.

00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:36.560
And in terms of distinguishing between MGUS and smoldering myeloma, we should remember

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:39.080
that smoldering myeloma is more common than we think.

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:47.620
In the I-STOP-MM study, half a percent of the people over 40 in Iceland were found to

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:49.900
have smoldering myeloma on this screening project.

00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:56.820
And using this online tool, when you have a patient, an asymptomatic patient with a monoclonal

00:00:56.820 --> 00:00:57.220
protein.

00:00:57.740 --> 00:01:02.240
It tells us about 40% of patients need a bone marrow biopsy.

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:07.820
And if you follow that rule, if you follow the recommendations from this tool, about

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:11.100
a third of the patients you biopsy will end up having smoldering myeloma.

00:01:11.460 --> 00:01:16.000
So it's important to think about this and not just assume everybody has MGUS.

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:20.160
And we know that not all smoldering myeloma is the same.

00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:23.220
The risk is not 10% across the board.

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:24.280
There are some patients.

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:27.720
This is the current IMWG risk strategy.

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:30.820
The 22-20 plus high-risk cytogenetics.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:37.760
And if you use those risk factors as continuous parameters, there's a subgroup that has as

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:43.740
high as a 72% risk at two years of progressing to symptomatic multiple myeloma.

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:53.400
There's also biological rationale for treating smoldering multiple myeloma, less acquired

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:55.720
resistance, less clonal heterogeneity.

00:01:57.740 --> 00:01:59.360
And then there's this.

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:01.320
There's patient-driven reasons, right?

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:06.840
So patients who pursue therapy for smoldering myeloma are a pretty self-selected group of

00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:07.220
patients.

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:11.380
Once you start talking about the data that we're going to review today, some of them

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:12.360
really want to be on therapy.

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:18.420
They can't accept the idea of doing nothing, even if their risk is not 72% at two years.

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:23.620
Some of them feel the need to do something, and that drives decision-making for all of

00:02:23.620 --> 00:02:23.780
us.

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:26.440
We're also entering, I would say, a

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:27.380
degeneration.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:27.380
We're also entering, I would say, a degeneration.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:27.380
We're also entering, I would say, a degeneration.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:27.380
We're also entering, I would say, a degeneration.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:27.380
We're also entering, I would say, a degeneration.

