We're also entering, I would say, a degeneration.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:32.300
A different era in terms of assessing risk, and this is coming pretty fast, right?

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:35.240
So molecular profiling, looking for other drivers.

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:41.060
This is work that was mostly done at Miami, but it was a national collaboration.

00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:48.180
They identified 20-something molecular factors, identifiable molecular factors, which drive

00:02:48.180 --> 00:02:48.660
risk.

00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:55.120
And then there were four of them, and maybe not surprising ones, the presence of RAS

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:56.500
mutations, APOBEC.

00:02:57.020 --> 00:03:05.800
profile MYC abnormalities also drive risk. And they use this model to sort of functionally

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:14.700
divide patients with asymptomatic plasma cell diseases into genomic myeloma and genomic MGUS.

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:19.960
And you can see here that even patients who were diagnosed with MGUS, some of them already have

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:25.680
the genomic profile that looks more like myeloma. So these patients may functionally be like

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:31.480
smoldering myeloma patients. So we don't need to spend a ton of time going over the few randomized

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:37.220
trials looking at smoldering myeloma. The first one was the QUERIDEX Spanish trial,

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:43.880
a somewhat problematic randomized trial based on when treatment was initiated in each arm,

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:50.800
how smoldering myeloma was defined. But at a 12-year follow-up publication,

00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:55.660
the difference in time to progression was seven years.

00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:56.340
The second one was a trial that was done in two arms. And the difference in time was seven years.

00:03:56.340 --> 00:03:56.640
And the second one was a trial that was done in two arms. And the difference in time was seven years.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:04:01.120
And the second one was a trial that was done in two arms. And even though early survival was

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:08.460
problematic and very concerning that the observation group had a survival more like myeloma,

00:04:08.460 --> 00:04:15.540
not like smoldering myeloma, ultimately, overall survival ended up being long for both groups,

00:04:15.660 --> 00:04:22.320
but different. And patients responded well to next line of therapy when they progressed,

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:25.660
regardless of which arm they were on. We also have the, you know, the, you know, the, you know,

00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:33.580
the ECOG study, which defined high-risk smoldering somewhat differently. More along the lines of how

00:04:33.580 --> 00:04:40.480
we think about it now, although not including cytogenetic risk as part of it. This was lenalidomide

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:46.600
alone versus observation. And this was len to progression. And not surprisingly, the len group

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:52.460
had longer time to progression. PFS was quite different. I think the thing, the important

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:55.460
thing to remember about this, and I think the thing we learned, this was,

00:04:55.680 --> 00:05:00.740
the len until progression, but only two-thirds of patients were still on therapy at one year.

00:05:00.740 --> 00:05:07.960
And of those two-thirds, 80% of them had had dose reductions already. And the delivered dose

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:13.700
intensity was 55% in that two-thirds who were still on treatment. So this really ended up being

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:22.460
finite therapy. And also the PFS difference was completely driven by the high-risk

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:25.660
smoldering myeloma group in this subset.

00:05:25.680 --> 00:05:29.920
And sort of established that only high-risk smoldering myeloma really ought to be treated,

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:37.220
not even intermediate risk. We have the AQUILA trial, which I think for patients changed thinking

00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:42.920
quite a bit. In my practice, I think I have more patients who've been interested in daratumumab

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:49.500
therapy than lenalidomide therapy. This was a randomization between DARA given in standard

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:55.300
fashion, sub-Q, versus observation. And we can see here that five-year progression-free survival,

00:05:55.300 --> 00:05:55.660
strong progression-free survival. And we have a lot of patients who have been interested in

00:05:55.680 --> 00:05:56.160
daratumumab therapy. And we have a lot of patients who have been interested in daratumumab therapy.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:06:03.580
And there was also a small difference in overall survival as well. And in the patients who

00:06:03.580 --> 00:06:09.840
progressed, the observation patients were more likely to have true CRAB progressions rather than

00:06:09.840 --> 00:06:19.000
slim CRAB biochemical progressions than in the DARA arm. So the current NCCN guidelines

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:25.060
recommend not treating lower intermediate risk at all. They recommend for high-risk patients,

00:06:25.060 --> 00:06:25.660
clinical trials, and high-risk patients. And they recommend for high-risk patients,

00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:31.480
clinical trials, when they're available, and somewhat favor DARA over lenalidomide. But those

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:36.800
are the two options that are being presented, that are basically being considered. And so

00:06:36.800 --> 00:06:41.780
we have to think about, so what are we trying to accomplish with therapy? And so there's kind of

00:06:41.780 --> 00:06:46.740
different philosophies, delay versus cure. And delay is you're trying to avoid overtreatment.

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:52.040
You're reluctant to treat patients and expose patients to risk who don't actually,

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:55.440
aren't going to progress. And so we're minimizing toxicity,

00:06:55.640 --> 00:06:59.580
and we're trying to avoid treatment-related deaths. Whereas the cure approach,

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:05.280
we're trying to eradicate disease, trying to tackle that pre-resistant

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:12.640
state. And there have been several studies looking at very intensive myeloma-like approaches

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:20.220
to treating smoldering. And these, unlike the trials I just showed you, are actually

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:25.080
making patients MRD negative at least half the time. And so,

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:30.420
potentially, I think has the, at least the potential to be eradicating disease. So here

00:07:30.420 --> 00:07:36.360
are my conclusions. We know there are some patients who should be treated. Our job right now

00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:42.040
is to give patients the data so that they can make decisions. And again, in my own practice,

00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:47.740
that seems to be daratumumab more often than lenalidomide. Clinical trials remain a top

00:07:47.740 --> 00:07:55.240
preference. And I'm just going to tee up the topic of the bispecifics, the BCMA-targeted therapies,

00:07:55.600 --> 00:08:02.600
you know, I showed you that scale, and it's always a choice between mild therapy that never

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:08.660
puts patients into an MRD state versus super-intensive therapy, which does. And you're

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:13.060
trying to decide which route do you want to go. We're about to enter an era where you don't have

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:19.020
to make that choice. We now have very tolerable therapies that are making patients MRD negative

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:25.580
quite quickly. And so, BCMA-targeted therapies are a great example of an approach that may

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:33.600
be the optimal approach for smoldering myeloma. And as we do this, in addition to studies

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:40.200
which explore new therapies, we should remember that our definition of risk continues to evolve

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:43.880
and we're entering a molecular era where we're going to be defining patients in that way

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:45.760
as well. And that's what I got. Thank you.
